# Cursor Subagent Architecture

## Two-tier agent system

This setup uses two agent directories that serve different purposes:

| Directory | Scope | Format | Special fields |
| --------- | ----- | ------ | -------------- |
| `~/.cursor/agents/` | Cursor-native (preferred) | YAML frontmatter + prompt | `model`, `readonly`, `is_background` |
| `~/.claude/agents/` | Claude Code compatible | YAML frontmatter + prompt | `model` only (Claude aliases) |

**Precedence:** When both directories contain an agent with the same name, `~/.cursor/agents/` wins.

## When to use each directory

### Use `~/.cursor/agents/` (Cursor-native) for:
- Agents that benefit from `model: fast` (lightweight tasks)
- Agents that are read-only reviewers (`readonly: true`)
- Agents that should run as background tasks (`is_background: true`)
- Any new agent you are creating for Cursor use

### Use `~/.claude/agents/` for:
- Agents that need to work in Claude Code CLI workflows
- Agents in the existing 87-agent Claude-compatible library
- Cross-tool compatibility requirements

## YAML frontmatter format (Cursor-native)

```markdown
---
name: agent-name
description: When to use this agent and what it does. Write this as if Agent is reading it to decide when to delegate. Be specific — vague descriptions prevent delegation.
model: fast | inherit | <specific-model-id>
readonly: true | false
is_background: false | true
---

Agent prompt body here.
```

## Model assignment policy

| Agent type | model value | Rationale |
| ---------- | ----------- | --------- |
| Recon / explore / search | `fast` | Read-only, speed > depth |
| Review / audit (readonly) | `inherit` | Needs parent model quality |
| Build / implement | `inherit` | Complex reasoning required |
| Verification / validation | `fast` | Structured, bounded task |
| Test runner | `fast` | Mechanical, not analytical |
| Security audits | `inherit` | Risk-sensitive, needs depth |
| Architecture review | `inherit` | Complex tradeoffs |

## Description writing guide

The `description` field is the primary signal Agent uses to decide when to delegate. Write it as:
- "Use when [specific situation]..."
- "Use proactively for [recurring trigger]..."
- Include concrete trigger phrases users might say

**Bad:** "A general coding helper"
**Good:** "Use when implementing backend endpoints, services, database queries, or async jobs. Use proactively when the task involves server-side code. Primary agent for all backend BUILD phase work."

## Readonly policy

Set `readonly: true` for agents that should NEVER modify files:
- Code reviewers
- Security auditors
- Architect reviewers
- Verifiers
- Research/exploration agents

Set `readonly: false` (default) for agents that implement:
- Developers (frontend, backend, fullstack)
- Test writers
- DevOps implementers
- Documentation engineers

## Background execution

Use `is_background: true` sparingly, only when:
- The agent's output is not needed immediately by the parent
- The task is long-running and the parent can continue without it
- The result will be read from disk by the parent later

Do NOT use background for:
- Agents whose output feeds the next phase
- Security reviews before BUILD
- Any critic/review phase agent

## Routing in ks-conductor

When the `Task` tool `model` parameter is used, it overrides the frontmatter `model`. Use the Task parameter when:
- You need to force `fast` for a cheap parallel recon fan-out
- You need a stronger model for a single high-stakes branch
- The frontmatter specifies something that does not match current needs

## Anti-patterns

- Do not create dozens of vague agents with generic descriptions
- Do not duplicate agents across both directories unnecessarily
- Do not use `is_background: true` for agents that gate the next phase
- Do not assign `model: fast` to security or architecture agents
- Do not set `readonly: true` for agents that need to write files to do their job
